abstract: SAN FRANCISCO, Aug. 6. -- United States steamer Charleston arrived here yesterday. The Charleston left here May 9 to go in pursuit of the Chilean insurgent steamer Itata, and returned with that vessel to San Diego, Cal., July 4. abstract: CARLYLE AND BORES. -- Carlyle did not know how to put up with bores. abstract: The death of George Jones, the proprietor of THE NEW-YORK TIMES, at Poland Springs, Me., is announced. He would have been eighty years old next Sunday. He was of slight figure and frail health, but of dauntless will and unfailing perseverance. It is difficult to discriminate between his character and that of the journal he has long controlled, and of which he was one of the founders.

abstract: MOBILE, Ala., Aug. 14. -- The crop reports from Middle and Southwest Alabama this week are very much mixed, and some difficulty is found in drawing any satisfactory conclusion from them. abstract: CHICAGO, Aug. 15. -- The session on the Board of Trade to-day was one of the wildest ever known on the floor. Greatly to the consternation of the bears, December wheat touched $1.08. They had been partly prepared for the boom Friday, but when the bulls took hold again and sent prices up once more they were dumfounded. Such jumps in the figures had not been seen since the days when Hutchinson was operating.

abstract: Frank White, who calls himself an ex-light-weight champion pugilist, does not like the idea of policemen carrying night sticks. abstract: TARRYTOWN, N.Y., Aug. 20. -- Mayor Chapin of Brooklyn, who is ill at the home of his relatives, the Schieffelins, in this place, is very much improved to-day. abstract: SPRINGFIELD, Mass., Aug. 23. -- Harper Brothers' Circus, billed for two performances at Thompsonville Saturday, came to grief in the evening. The performers struck about 8 o'clock for back wages. It was announced that there would be no performance and money would be refunded. The crowd became excited, cut the guy ropes, set the tent on fire, smashed seats and wagons, and cut up harness.

The Lebanon Valley Branch of the Reading Railroad between this city and Lebanon is badly crippled.

abstract: INDEPENDENCE, Iowa, Aug. 27. -- The racing here to-day was something phenomenal, for the 30,000 people present saw fourteen miles trotted or paced no one being in slower time than 3:21 3/4. Nancy Hanks, in the five-year-old class, put to her credit the three fastest heats ever trotted in a race, and reduced her record by two seconds and a half, and Roy Wilkes paced the three fastest heats to the credit of a stallion.
